Pipeline starts with domain types: listing.go, deal.go, product.go 

1. DOMAIN TYPES 
listing.go: 
    raw data from marketplace adapters
    output of normalization
    condition scale
    computed baseline sold price for a "product:condition_tier"


*contracts established by listing.go * 
adapters produce RawListing
normalization produces NormalizedListing
pricing produces PriceSnapshot

deal.go:
    defines pricing and alerting models
    DealCandidate - scored version of an active listing
    TierThresholds - good/great/excellent

    *contracts established by deal.go *
    Score(priceUSD, baselineUSD) - the.... scoring contract 

product.go 
    catalog and watchlist side 
    later stages will rely on these for identity, rules, MarkAlertSent

2. INGEST BOUNDARY

source.go - generic marketplace interface - not just ebay-specific

Implemented adapter boundary is: adapter.go . Entry point for market fetches. Routing:
active listings -> browse client
sold listings -> finding client 

therefore

active listings feed deal discovery and sold listings feed pricing history 


3. Normalization pipeline

Three layers.
mapper.go 
    Resolve()
        Hardcoded mappings for ebay condition strings
        Keywords overrides for ignoring items (broken/not working/for parts)
        Downgrade keywords (scratches, wear)
    
rules.go : entity resolution from the title. Normalizes titles, sorts rule


example

rules := []MatchRule{
    {
        Name:               "sony-generic",
        CanonicalProductID: idA,
        RequiredKeywords:   []string{"sony", "85mm"},
        MatchMode:          MatchModeAll,
        Priority:           5,
    },
    {
        Name:               "sony-fe-85",
        CanonicalProductID: idB,
        RequiredKeywords:   []string{"sony", "fe", "85mm"},
        MatchMode:          MatchModeAll,
        Priority:           5,
    },
    {
        Name:               "sony-any-portrait",
        CanonicalProductID: idC,
        RequiredKeywords:   []string{"sony", "85mm", "portrait"},
        MatchMode:          MatchModeAny,
        Priority:           20,
    },
}
            Step 1: Sort by priority

                sony-any-portrait has priority 20
                the other two have priority 5
            Step 2. If two are equal priority, sort by the number of matching RequiredKeywords. sony-fe-85 and sony-generic:
                -both have priority 5
                -sony-fe-85 has 3 required keywords, the other has 2. sony-fe-85 comes before sony-generic

            
ANOTHER EXAMPLE WITH EXCLUDED Keywords

{
    Name:               "canon-rf-50",
    CanonicalProductID: idX,
    RequiredKeywords:   []string{"canon", "50mm"},
    ExcludedKeywords:   []string{"fd"},
    MatchMode:          MatchModeAll,
    Priority:           10,
}

rulematches checks ExcludedKeywords first... fails immediately. Returns no match. 

Tie breaker: which has less text... and which title is smaller 

in short: 
Normalize the title
Copy and sort the rules
For each rule in sorted order:
reject if an excluded phrase matches
check required keywords using "all" or "any"
if it matches, return that product ID and confidence immediately
If none match, return nil, 0